## Test Scenario 5 — AI Processing Pipeline

> [!WARNING]
> Processing triggers the full 9-step AI pipeline. This can take **1–3 minutes** depending on AI model response times.

| # | Step | Expected Result |
|---|------|-----------------|
| 1 | On the batch card, click the **"Process"** button | Processing begins — button disappears |
| 2 | Watch the status pill change through stages | Status transitions through: `Uploading` → `Parsing` → `Analyzing` → `Anonymizing` → `Matching` → `Ranking` → `Explaining` → `Final Check` → **`Complete`** |
| 3 | Each active processing stage shows a **pulsing dot** | Animated dot visible in the colored status pill |
| 4 | Wait for processing to complete | Status pill turns green: **"Complete"** |
| 5 | Verify **fairness scores** appear on the batch card | Shows `Before → After` scores (e.g., `62 → 91`) |
| 6 | Check `StatsRow` updates | Stats reflect 1 batch, 2 candidates processed |

### What the Pipeline Does to the Test Resumes

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A["📄 Upload PDFs"] --> B["📝 Parse Resumes"]
    B --> C["📊 Bias Analysis (Before)"]
    C --> D["🔒 Anonymize Data"]
    D --> E["🎯 Skill Matching vs JD"]
    E --> F["📈 Ranking"]
    F --> G["💬 Generate Explanations"]
    G --> H["📊 Bias Analysis (After)"]
    H --> I["✅ Complete"]

    style A fill:#EEF2FF,stroke:#6366F1
    style D fill:#F3E8FF,stroke:#A855F7
    style I fill:#ECFDF5,stroke:#10B981
```

**Aarav Sharma's resume** (41 KB — detailed):
- Rich content with full experience, projects, skills, education
- Should parse completely → higher skill match if aligned with JD
- Name, college, location will be anonymized (e.g. → `C-101`)

**Priya Mehta's resume** (2 KB — concise):
- Minimal content, fewer details
- May produce a lower match score due to less extractable data
- Same anonymization treatment → fair comparison on skill alone

