## Test Scenario 6 — Candidate Ranking View

| # | Step | Expected Result |
|---|------|-----------------|
| 1 | Click the **completed batch card** | Batch details load: candidates + bias report fetched in parallel |
| 2 | Switch to the **"Candidates"** tab | `CandidateList` renders with 2 candidate cards |
| 3 | Verify header shows batch title (extracted from JD) | e.g., "Full Stack Developer" |
| 4 | Verify subheader | "Ranked by skill match — anonymized for fair evaluation" |
| 5 | Verify badge shows count | "2 ranked" |
| 6 | **Candidate Card #1** (higher rank) | Shows: anonymized ID (e.g., `C-101`), match score, rank badge, skill breakdown |
| 7 | **Candidate Card #2** (lower rank) | Same structure, lower match score |
| 8 | Verify **skill breakdown** on each card | Lists matched/unmatched skills with confidence levels |
| 9 | Verify **explanation text** | AI-generated explanation of why this candidate was ranked at this position |
| 10 | Confirm candidates are **anonymized** | No real names, college names, or locations visible |

### Expected Ranking Behavior

| Resume | Likely Score | Reasoning |
|--------|-------------|-----------|
| Aarav Sharma (41 KB) | **Higher** | More detailed resume → more skills extracted → higher match potential |
| Priya Mehta (2 KB) | **Lower** | Concise resume → fewer extractable skills → lower match confidence |

> [!TIP]
> The ranking should be purely skill-based. The fact that one resume is more detailed doesn't mean bias — it means more data for the AI to match. The bias report (Scenario 7) validates this.

